Value.value: These books contain information about the "Bastion Wars". This was a war between angels and demons that occurred in the Actand region, fought over strange pretenses and mysterious artifacts. The Rising Sun cult formed after the disappearance of the outsiders, worshiping whatever source of the war existed, believing they were chosen as heirs to a new, "Purer" Amia.
These books contain information about the "Bastion Wars", which seem to be wars between angels and demons. The Rising Sun Cult formed in the wake of their disappearance to carry on their work.

These books details the "Bastion Wars" of Actand, between a nameless council of Celestial Commanders, and the army of the demon Ks'say Everlast. They fought over eldritch relics and ancient mystic locuses of magic on the island and the area. Following their expulsion at the hands of Halaster Blackcloak, the Rising Sun cult formed to scavenge what was left of the war, and carry out what they believed the Outsiders' true purpose was: To scourge the land through war and bring about a new Amia tested by fire, and in worship of the eldritch and immaterial.

Of interesting note is that Ks'say Everlast, leader of the demonic outsiders, is also famously the demon summoned and involved in the island of Caraigh's near destruction and subsequent tainting, summoned by Lord Blackmoor.

Value.value: This shrine looks like it's dedicated to various angelic creatures, and in front of it are a few rusted swords and blade that still gleam and glitter in the torchlight of the caverns.

This shrine is dedicated to the Celestial Council of Actand, and their cleansing, purging war against the Demons in Actand. The objects around the shrine look to be scavenged Celestial objects and relics from the ocean around the area, but none of them seem inherently powerful or magical.

A Shrine here to the Celestial Council of Actand is clearly postured in warlike poses, much more malicious than any statue to angels has a right to be. This reflects the Risen Sun's philosophy of purging and cleansing through war, and remaking the world from its ashes. The objects are venerated by the cult, and a few look usable, if mostly mundane. It would likely be a great honor to be allowed to wield them on the part of the cult.

Strangely, the celestial theming continues throughout the area, and although fashioned against the Demons on a thematic level, on a deeper level it's intentionally stylized to make the two opposing sides look as though they're working towards the same purpose.

Value.value: This shrine is dedicated to the Demonic warriors who held siege outside Actand on small fortified islands. The collected objects glimmer with malice, and must have been scavenged from the area.

This shrine is dedicated to the leader of the Demons, "Everlast", and their "Claimant War", so called by the cultists against the angels. The objects around the shrine looks demonic in nature, and you can practically feel the vile energy pulsing off of them, althoug hin their current state, none of them look much more than mundane, despite the feeling of dead.

Dedicated to Ks'say Everlast, commander of the Demonic Armies, this shrine is a clear marker of the Cult's dual-natured worship. Believing the war against the angels was part of a larger plan to raze Amia and raise up a new land made in the eldritch image of the Outsiders is a keystone of the Cult's beliefs. The objects laid around the shrine are used towards this strange belief and purpose, and it would be a high honor in the cult to be allowed to wield them.

Believing the war against the angels was part of a larger plan to raze Amia and raise up a new land made in the eldritch image of the Outsiders is a keystone of the Cult's beliefs. The objects laid around the shrine are used towards this strange belief and purpose, and it would be a high honor in the cult to be allowed to wield them. The demonic theming continues throughout the cave, poising them against the angels, but never quite as spectacularly as perhaps they should be. On a more grand level, it's made to look as though both sides were striving together for the same purpose. A strange and deeply heretical belief on all sides.
